nya | publisher = RSS weekly publication| language = Hindi}}\n* {{cite news | url =http://www.organiser.org/ | title = Organiser | publisher = RSS weekly publication}}\n* {{citation |title= Bunch of Thoughts |url= http://www.golwalkarguruji.org/shri-guruji/thoughts/bunch-of-thoughts-book |year= 1966 |publisher= Sahitya Sindhu Prakashan |location= Bangalore, India |isbn= 81-86595-19-8 |access-date= 29 October 2006 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070128012427/http://www.golwalkarguruji.org/shri-guruji/thoughts/bunch-of-thoughts-book |archive-date= 28 January 2007 |url-status=dead |df= dmy-all }} (A Collection of Speeches by Golwalkar).\n* [http://www.eswastika.com/ Weekly Swastika] (A Nationalist Bengali News Weekly)\n* {{citation| url =http://archivesofrss.org/index.php?option=com_biographies&Itemid=37/ | title = Biographies of Dr. Hedgewar The founder of RSS| language = Hindi, English}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Sangh Parivar}}\n{{Hindu Nationalism}}\n{{The Emergency (India)}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh}}\n[[Category:Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Hindutva]]\n[[Category:Hindu nationalism]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1925]]\n[[Category:Sangh Parivar]]\n[[Category:Volunteer organisations in India]]\n[[Category:Paramilitary organisations based in India]]\n", "name_user": "Achint2182", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed invalid citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rashtriya_Swayamsevak_Sangh"}
{"title_page": "Tang Yijun", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name = Tang Yijun\n|native_name = {{lang|zh|{{nobold|\u5510\u4e00\u519b}}}}\n|image = \n|caption = \n|office1       = [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]]\n|term_start1   = 29 April 2020\n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = [[Fu Zhenghua]]\n|successor1    = \n|1blankname1   = Prime Minister\n|1namedata1    = [[Li Keqiang]]\n|office2       = [[Politics of Liaoning|Governor]] of [[Liaoning]]\n|term_start2   = October 2017\n|term_end2     = April 2020\n|predecessor2  = [[Chen Qiufa]]\n|successor2    = \n|office3       = Deputy Party Secretary of [[Zhejiang]]\n|term_start3   = May 2017\n|term_end3     = October 2017\n|predecessor3  = [[Yuan Jiajun]]\n|successor3    = Zheng Shanjie\n|office4       = Party Secretary of [[Ningbo]]\n|term_start4   = August 2016\n|term_end4     = October 2017\n|predecessor4  = [[Liu Qi (politician, born 1957)|Liu Qi]]\n|successor4    = Zheng Shanjie\n|office5       = Mayor of Ningbo\n|term_start5   = May 2016 \n|term_end5     = February 2017\n|predecessor5  = [[Lu Ziyue]]\n|successor5    = Qiu Dongyao\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1961|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Ju County]], Shandong, China\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|party = [[Communist Party of China]]\n|spouse = \n|children = \n|alma_mater = [[Central Party School of the Communist Party of China]]\n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u5510|\u4e00|\u519b}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u5510|\u4e00|\u8ecd}}\n|p = T\u00e1ng Y\u012bj\u016bn \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Tang (surname)|Tang]]}}\n'''Tang Yijun''' ({{zh|s=\u5510\u4e00\u519b|p=T\u00e1ng Y\u012bj\u016bn}}; born March 1961) is a Chinese politician, and the current [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]]. He formerly served as Governor of [[northeast China]]'s [[Liaoning]] province. Prior to his transfer to Liaoning in October 2017, he spent his entire career in [[Zhejiang]] province. He was the mayor, then party chief of Ningbo.\n\n==Biography==\nTang is considered native to [[Ju County]], Shandong, but spent most of his life in Zhejiang. He joined the workforce in July 1977, working for communes in [[Qingtian County]], [[Yongkang County]], and [[Liandu District|Lishui County]], shortly after the death of Mao. Between 1980 and 1984, shortly after economic reforms began, Tang was a clerical worker at the Lishui party school; he was admitted to the Zhejiang party school in 1984, and was assigned work in the propaganda department of Zhejiang.\n\nIn October 1985, Tang joined the Communist Party of China. In 1991, Tang began working for the General Office of the Zhejiang party committee under [[Li Zemin]]. In July 1997, he became secretary-general of the [[Zhoushan]] party organization. In June 2002, he was named secretary-general of the Zhejiang Commission for Discipline Inspection. In June 2005, he was named deputy party chief and Discipline Inspection secretary of Ningbo. In February 2010, he became the chief of the Political and Legal Affairs Commission of Ningbo. In February 2011, he was named chairman of the Ningbo People's Political Consultative Conference.<ref name=gbzl>{{cite web|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u9886\u5bfc\u5e72\u90e8\u8d44\u6599\u5e93\uff1a\u5510\u4e00\u519b| language=zh|url=http://gbzl.people.com.cn/grzy.php?id=160500001|work=people.com.cn|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Tang was named mayor of Ningbo.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=zh:\u5510\u4e00\u519b\u4efb\u5b81\u6ce2\u5e02\u4ee3\u5e02\u957f| language=zh|url=http://news.ifeng.com/a/20160506/48698326_0.shtml|work=ifeng.com|date=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\nIn August 2016, he became Communist Party Secretary of Ningbo and a member of the Zhejiang [[provincial party standing committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_1518921|script-title=zh:\u4ece\u5b81\u6ce2\u653f\u534f\u4e3b\u5e2d\u5230\u4ee3\u5e02\u957f\u518d\u5230\u5e02\u59d4\u4e66\u8bb0\uff0c\u5510\u4e00\u519b\u7f55\u89c1\u8eab\u6311\u4e09\u804c| language=zh|work=thepaper.cn|accessdate=2016-08-24}}</ref> In May 2017, Tang was named deputy party chief of Zhejiang province. He served in the role for five months before being appointed as acting governor of Liaoning in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://district.ce.cn/newarea/sddy/201705/03/t20170503_22500476.shtml | language=zh |script-title=zh:\u5510\u4e00\u519b\u4efb\u6d59\u6c5f\u7701\u59d4\u526f\u4e66\u8bb0(\u7b80\u5386) |work=ce.cn |date=May 3, 2017|accessdate= }}</ref> On April 29, 2020, he was appointed [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]], replacing [[Fu Zhenghua]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-before|before= [[Lu Ziyue]]}}\n{{s-title|title= Mayor of Ningbo\n|years=2016-2017}}\n{{s-after|after= Qiu Dongyao ({{lang|zh|\u88d8\u4e1c\u8000}})}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chen Qiufa]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Politics of Liaoning|Governor]] of [[Liaoning]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-after|after=TAB}}\n{{s-before|before=[[Fu Zhenghua]]}}\n{{s-title|title= [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]]\n|years=2020}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Liu Qi (born 1957)|Liu Qi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Communist Party Secretary]] of [[Ningbo]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zheng Zhajie]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Yuan Jiajun]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy Party Secretary]] of [[Zhejiang]]|years=2017-2017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zheng Zhajie]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Regional leaders in the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Liaoning leaders}}\n\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of China politicians from Shandong]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Shandong]]\n[[Category:Governors of Liaoning]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Ningbo]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name = Tang Yijun\n|native_name = {{lang|zh|{{nobold|\u5510\u4e00\u519b}}}}\n|image = \n|caption = \n|office1       = [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]]\n|term_start1   = 29 April 2020\n|term_end1     = \n|predecessor1  = [[Fu Zhenghua]]\n|successor1    = \n|1blankname1   = Prime Minister\n|1namedata1    = [[Li Keqiang]]\n|office2       = [[Politics of Liaoning|Governor]] of [[Liaoning]]\n|term_start2   = October 2017\n|term_end2     = April 2020\n|predecessor2  = [[Chen Qiufa]]\n|successor2    = \n|office3       = Deputy Party Secretary of [[Zhejiang]]\n|term_start3   = May 2017\n|term_end3     = October 2017\n|predecessor3  = [[Yuan Jiajun]]\n|successor3    = Zheng Shanjie\n|office4       = Party Secretary of [[Ningbo]]\n|term_start4   = August 2016\n|term_end4     = October 2017\n|predecessor4  = [[Liu Qi (politician, born 1957)|Liu Qi]]\n|successor4    = Zheng Shanjie\n|office5       = Mayor of Ningbo\n|term_start5   = May 2016 \n|term_end5     = February 2017\n|predecessor5  = [[Lu Ziyue]]\n|successor5    = Qiu Dongyao\n|birth_date = {{birth year and age|1961|3}}\n|birth_place = [[Ju County]], Shandong, China\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|party = [[Communist Party of China]]\n|spouse = \n|children = \n|alma_mater = [[Central Party School of the Communist Party of China]]\n| module  = {{Infobox Chinese|child=yes\n|s = {{linktext|\u5510|\u4e00|\u519b}}\n|t = {{linktext|\u5510|\u4e00|\u8ecd}}\n|p = T\u00e1ng Y\u012bj\u016bn \n|w = \n}}\n}}\n{{Chinese name|[[Tang (surname)|Tang]]}}\n'''Tang Yijun''' ({{zh|s=\u5510\u4e00\u519b|p=T\u00e1ng Y\u012bj\u016bn}}; born March 1961) is a Chinese politician, and the current [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]]. He formerly served as Governor of [[northeast China]]'s [[Liaoning]] province. Prior to his transfer to Liaoning in October 2017, he spent his entire career in [[Zhejiang]] province. He was the mayor, then party chief of Ningbo.\n\n==Biography==\nTang is considered native to [[Ju County]], Shandong, but spent most of his life in Zhejiang. He joined the workforce in July 1977, working for communes in [[Qingtian County]], [[Yongkang County]], and [[Liandu District|Lishui County]], shortly after the death of Mao. Between 1980 and 1984, shortly after economic reforms began, Tang was a clerical worker at the Lishui party school; he was admitted to the Zhejiang party school in 1984, and was assigned work in the propaganda department of Zhejiang.\n\nIn October 1985, Tang joined the Communist Party of China. In 1991, Tang began working for the General Office of the Zhejiang party committee under [[Li Zemin]]. In July 1997, he became secretary-general of the [[Zhoushan]] party organization. In June 2002, he was named secretary-general of the Zhejiang Commission for Discipline Inspection. In June 2005, he was named deputy party chief and Discipline Inspection secretary of Ningbo. In February 2010, he became the chief of the Political and Legal Affairs Commission of Ningbo. In February 2011, he was named chairman of the Ningbo People's Political Consultative Conference.<ref name=gbzl>{{cite web|script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\u9886\u5bfc\u5e72\u90e8\u8d44\u6599\u5e93\uff1a\u5510\u4e00\u519b| language=zh|url=http://gbzl.people.com.cn/grzy.php?id=160500001|work=people.com.cn|accessdate=July 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, Tang was named mayor of Ningbo.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=zh:\u5510\u4e00\u519b\u4efb\u5b81\u6ce2\u5e02\u4ee3\u5e02\u957f| language=zh|url=http://news.ifeng.com/a/20160506/48698326_0.shtml|work=ifeng.com|date=May 6, 2016}}</ref>\nIn August 2016, he became Communist Party Secretary of Ningbo and a member of the Zhejiang [[provincial party standing committee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepaper.cn/newsDetail_forward_1518921|script-title=zh:\u4ece\u5b81\u6ce2\u653f\u534f\u4e3b\u5e2d\u5230\u4ee3\u5e02\u957f\u518d\u5230\u5e02\u59d4\u4e66\u8bb0\uff0c\u5510\u4e00\u519b\u7f55\u89c1\u8eab\u6311\u4e09\u804c| language=zh|work=thepaper.cn|accessdate=2016-08-24}}</ref> In May 2017, Tang was named deputy party chief of Zhejiang province. He served in the role for five months before being appointed as acting governor of Liaoning in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://district.ce.cn/newarea/sddy/201705/03/t20170503_22500476.shtml | language=zh |script-title=zh:\u5510\u4e00\u519b\u4efb\u6d59\u6c5f\u7701\u59d4\u526f\u4e66\u8bb0(\u7b80\u5386) |work=ce.cn |date=May 3, 2017|accessdate= }}</ref> On April 29, 2020, he was appointed [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]], replacing [[Fu Zhenghua]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-before|before= [[Lu Ziyue]]}}\n{{s-title|title= Mayor of Ningbo\n|years=2016-2017}}\n{{s-after|after= Qiu Dongyao ({{lang|zh|\u88d8\u4e1c\u8000}})}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chen Qiufa]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Politics of Liaoning|Governor]] of [[Liaoning]]|years=2017\u20132020}}\n{{s-after|after=TAB}}\n{{s-before|before=[[Fu Zhenghua]]}}\n{{s-title|title= [[Ministry of Justice of the People's Republic of China|Minister of Justice]]\n|years=2020}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Liu Qi (born 1957)|Liu Qi]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Communist Party Secretary]] of [[Ningbo]]|years=2016\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zheng Zhajie]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Yuan Jiajun]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Deputy Party Secretary]] of [[Zhejiang]]|years=2017-2017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Zheng Zhajie]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Regional leaders in the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Liaoning leaders}}\n\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of China politicians from Shandong]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Shandong]]\n[[Category:Governors of Liaoning]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Ningbo]]\n", "name_user": "Huangdan2060", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tang_Yijun"}
{"title_page": "Sister Souljah moment", "text_new": "In [[United States]] [[politics]], a '''Sister Souljah moment''' is a [[politician]]'s public repudiation of an [[extremism|extremist]] person or group, statement, or position perceived to have some association with the politician or the politician's party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianapolisrecorder.com/opinion/article_1e23b4da-0dd2-11e4-bdd5-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Time for a 'Sister Souljah' moment|date=July 17, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt has been described as \"a key moment when the candidate takes what at least appears to be a bold stand against certain extremes in their party\"<ref>{{cite web|authorlink=\"http://www.blogger.com/profile/06219319435229314554\"|url=http://notenoughtequila.blogspot.com/2012/03/mitts-sister-souljah-moment.html|title=Mitt's Sister Souljah Moment|date=March 5, 2012|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref> and as \"a calculated denunciation of an extremist position or special interest group.\"<ref name=BG/> Such an act of repudiation is designed to signal to [[centrism|centrist]] [[vote]]rs that the politician is not beholden to traditional, and sometimes unpopular, interest groups associated with the party,{{Citation needed|date=February 2013|reason=starting with \"designed to signal\u2026,\" another direct quote from Taegan Goddard's Political Dictionary, cited above}} although such a repudiation runs the risk of alienating some of the politician's allies and the party's [[Base (politics)|base]] voters. The term is named after the hip hop artist [[Sister Souljah]].<ref name=BG>{{cite web|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|title=Sister Souljah moments|first=Joan|last=Vennochi|date=September 16, 2007|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2007/09/16/sister_souljah_moments/}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Sister Souljah million womans march Philadelphia.jpg|thumb|upright|Sister Souljah in 1997]]\nThe term originated in the [[U.S. presidential election, 1992|1992 presidential]] candidacy of [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name=BG/>  In a ''[[Washington Post]]'' interview published on May 13, 1992, the [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] [[rapping|MC]], author, and [[political activist]] [[Sister Souljah]] was quoted as saying (in response to the question regarding black-on-white violence in the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]]):\n\n{{quote|Question: Even the people themselves who were perpetrating that violence, did they think that was wise? Was that a wise reasoned action?\n<br />\nSouljah: Yeah, it was wise. I mean, if black people kill black people every day, why not have a week and kill white people?... White people, this government and that mayor were well aware of the fact that black people were dying every day in Los Angeles under gang violence. So if you're a gang member and you would normally be killing somebody, why not kill a white person? Do you think that somebody thinks that white people are better, are above and beyond dying, when they would kill their own kind?|Quoted in David Mills (16 June 1992) \"In Her Own Disputed Words; Transcript of Interview That Spawned Souljah's Story\"|''The Washington Post''<ref>[[David Mills (TV writer)|David Mills]].  \"[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/31/AR2010033101709.html Sister Souljah's Call to Arms].'  ''Washington Post'', May 13, 1992, p. B1.</ref>}}\n\nSpeaking to [[Jesse Jackson, Sr.]]'s [[Rainbow/PUSH|Rainbow Coalition]] in June 1992, Clinton responded both to that quotation and to something Souljah had said in the music video of her song \"The Final Solution: Slavery's back in Effect\" (\"If there are any good white people, I haven't met them\").<ref>Anthony Lewis. '\"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE6DD1031F93BA25755C0A964958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print Abroad at Home; Black and White],\" ''New York Times''.</ref> \"If you took the words 'white' and 'black,' and you reversed them, you might think [[David Duke]] was giving that speech,\" said Clinton.\n\nPrior to his appearance, Clinton's campaign staff had conducted an intense debate about how far he should go in distancing himself from Jackson, who was unpopular with moderate voters. When Souljah was invited to speak at the conference, Clinton's advisors saw their chance.\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?26613-1/rap-artists-response-clinton-remarks Sister Souljah's response to Gov. Bill Clinton's remarks, June 16, 1992], [[C-SPAN]]}}\nClinton's response was harshly criticized by Jackson, who said, \"Sister Souljah represents the feelings and hopes of a whole generation of people,\" and he claimed that she had been misquoted.<ref>Lewis, ''Op.cit.''</ref> Clinton was also criticized by some of the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]'s other [[African American]] supporters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kornacki |first=Steve |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/1992-bill-clinton-builds-winning-coalition-jackson-diminished-n1029606 |title=1992: Bill Clinton builds a winning coalition, Jackson is diminished |work=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-07-29 |accessdate=2019-10-08 |quote=It was against this backdrop that Clinton delivered his \"Sister Souljah\" speech, which opened up a public war with Jackson. }}</ref> Souljah responded by denying she had ever made remarks promoting murder and accused Clinton of being a racist and a hypocrite because he had played golf at a country club that refused to admit black members until he decided to run for president earlier in the year;<ref name=uoooavt4>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-06-17/entertainment/ca-573_1_sister-souljah|title='I Do Not Advocate ... Murdering' : 'Raptivist' Sister Souljah Disputes Clinton Charge|author=Chuck Phillips|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=June 17, 1992|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> Clinton acknowledged that he was once a member of an all-white Arkansas golf club early into his presidential campaign and publicly apologized.<ref name=uoooavt4 />  In response to the rebuttal, [[Paul Greenberg (journalist)|Paul Greenberg]], a progressive Arkansas journalist and longtime Clinton critic who dubbed the Arkansas Governor \"Slick Willie\" during his 1980 re-election bid,<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/choice/bill/greenberg.html American Frontline:Stories of Bill] Accessed August 25, 2014</ref> criticized Souljah for lying about what she said in an earlier interview with the Washington Post, accusing her of trying to fend off criticism \"with the savvy of an experienced pol.\" In the same article he compares her to [[Louis Farrakhan]], the leader of the [[Nation of Islam]].<ref>\n{{citation|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-06-19/news/9202240214_1_context-moral-rationality|title=Sister Souljah And The Irrational Rationality Of Hate|author=Paul Greenberg|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=June 19, 1992|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Other examples==\nAs a [[candidate]] for the [[Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2000|Republican nomination for president in 2000]], [[Governor of Texas|Texas Governor]] [[George W. Bush]] spoke before the [[American conservatism|conservative]] [[Manhattan Institute]] in October 1999 saying, \"Too often, on social issues, my party has painted an image of America slouching toward Gomorrah,\" quoting the title of a [[Slouching Towards Gomorrah|book]] by conservative [[jurist]] [[Robert Bork]].  Bush's comments were seen as a repudiation of the religious right and an attempt to appeal to moderate voters; commentator [[Charles Krauthammer]] called it \"an ever so subtle Sister Souljah on Robert Bork.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-10-11/news/9910110132_1_slouching-towards-gomorrah-borkian-robert-bork|title=Setting Himself Apart From Those Hard-core Conservatives|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=2017-09-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlso in the 2000 campaign for the Republican nomination, [[Arizona]] [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John McCain]] stated, \"Neither party should be defined by pandering to the outer reaches of American politics and the agents of intolerance, whether they be [[Louis Farrakhan]] or [[Al Sharpton]] on the left or [[Pat Robertson]] or [[Jerry Falwell]] on the right.\" This was similarly seen as a repudiation of the religious right; columnist [[Jacob Weisberg]] called it \"a pungent Sister Souljah moment.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weisberg|first1=Jacob|title=McCain's Selective Outrage|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/ballot_box/2000/02/mccains_selective_outrage.html|website=Slate|publisher=Slate|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2008 United States presidential campaign]], [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee [[Barack Obama]] received much criticism for his association with his longtime Pastor [[Jeremiah Wright]], and Wright's pattern of racist statements. On April 29, Senator Obama distanced himself, in a well-received speech on racism, calling some of Wright's statements \"outrageous\" and \"a bunch of rants that aren't grounded in truth.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/29/AR2008042903173.html?hpid=topnews&hpid=topnews | work=The Washington Post | first1=Peter | last1=Slevin | first2=Darryl | last2=Fears | title=Obama Calls Minister's Comments 'Outrageous' | date=April 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Timraos\">Nick Timiraos and Jackie Calmes. ''Obama Denounces Ex-Pastor for 'Rants''', Wednesday, April 30, 2008, ppA1, A18.</ref> [[South Carolina]] [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] [[James Clyburn]] said of the speech, \"This, I think, offers Barack Obama his Sister Souljah moment\";<ref name=\"Timraos\"/> the speech was also described as \"more than a Sister Souljah moment\" by columnist [[Maureen Dowd]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/30/opinion/30dowd.html?_r=1&hp&oref=slogin | work=The New York Times | first=Maureen | last=Dowd | title=Praying and Preying | date=April 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn July 10, 2008, prior to a taping of ''[[Fox and Friends]]'', civil-rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]] was unwittingly caught by an open microphone whispering to a fellow interviewee, saying that then-candidate [[Barack Obama]] was talking down to black people and that he, Jackson, wanted to cut Obama's \"nuts off\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2008-07-09/politics/jesse.jackson.comment_1_obama-campaign-jesse-jackson-black-voters?_s=PM:POLITICS|title=Jackson apologizes for 'crude' Obama remarks|date=July 9, 2008|work=CNN Politics|accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref>  Jackson's son, Rep. [[Jesse Jackson, Jr.|Jesse Jackson Jr.]] of Illinois\u2014co-chair of Obama's presidential campaign\u2014publicly blasted his father's comments. [[Dan Balz]] called the comments an \"accidental Sister Souljah moment\" for Obama, since Jackson had distanced himself from the candidate, without Obama having to take a stand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2008/07/obamas-accidental-sister-soulj.html|title=Obama's Accidental Sister Souljah Moment|last=Balz|first=Dan|date=July 10, 2008|work=Washington Post|accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sister Souljah Moment}}\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n[[Category:American political neologisms]]\n[[Category:Extremism]]\n[[Category:Centrism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bill Clinton]]\n[[Category:1992 in American politics]]\n[[Category:History of hip hop]]\n[[Category:1992 Los Angeles riots]]\n", "text_old": "In [[United States]] [[politics]], a '''Sister Souljah moment''' is a [[politician]]'s public repudiation of an [[extremism|extremist] person or group, statement, or position perceived to have some association with the politician or the politician's party.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indianapolisrecorder.com/opinion/article_1e23b4da-0dd2-11e4-bdd5-001a4bcf887a.html|title=Time for a 'Sister Souljah' moment|date=July 17, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIt has been described as \"a key moment when the candidate takes what at least appears to be a bold stand against certain extremes in their party\"<ref>{{cite web|authorlink=\"http://www.blogger.com/profile/06219319435229314554\"|url=http://notenoughtequila.blogspot.com/2012/03/mitts-sister-souljah-moment.html|title=Mitt's Sister Souljah Moment|date=March 5, 2012|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref> and as \"a calculated denunciation of an extremist position or special interest group.\"<ref name=BG/> Such an act of repudiation is designed to signal to [[centrism|centrist]] [[vote]]rs that the politician is not beholden to traditional, and sometimes unpopular, interest groups associated with the party,{{Citation needed|date=February 2013|reason=starting with \"designed to signal\u2026,\" another direct quote from Taegan Goddard's Political Dictionary, cited above}} although such a repudiation runs the risk of alienating some of the politician's allies and the party's [[Base (politics)|base]] voters. The term is named after the hip hop artist [[Sister Souljah]].<ref name=BG>{{cite web|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|title=Sister Souljah moments|first=Joan|last=Vennochi|date=September 16, 2007|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2007/09/16/sister_souljah_moments/}}</ref>\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Sister Souljah million womans march Philadelphia.jpg|thumb|upright|Sister Souljah in 1997]]\nThe term originated in the [[U.S. presidential election, 1992|1992 presidential]] candidacy of [[Bill Clinton]].<ref name=BG/>  In a ''[[Washington Post]]'' interview published on May 13, 1992, the [[Hip hop music|hip-hop]] [[rapping|MC]], author, and [[political activist]] [[Sister Souljah]] was quoted as saying (in response to the question regarding black-on-white violence in the [[1992 Los Angeles riots]]):\n\n{{quote|Question: Even the people themselves who were perpetrating that violence, did they think that was wise? Was that a wise reasoned action?\n<br />\nSouljah: Yeah, it was wise. I mean, if black people kill black people every day, why not have a week and kill white people?... White people, this government and that mayor were well aware of the fact that black people were dying every day in Los Angeles under gang violence. So if you're a gang member and you would normally be killing somebody, why not kill a white person? Do you think that somebody thinks that white people are better, are above and beyond dying, when they would kill their own kind?|Quoted in David Mills (16 June 1992) \"In Her Own Disputed Words; Transcript of Interview That Spawned Souljah's Story\"|''The Washington Post''<ref>[[David Mills (TV writer)|David Mills]].  \"[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/03/31/AR2010033101709.html Sister Souljah's Call to Arms].'  ''Washington Post'', May 13, 1992, p. B1.</ref>}}\n\nSpeaking to [[Jesse Jackson, Sr.]]'s [[Rainbow/PUSH|Rainbow Coalition]] in June 1992, Clinton responded both to that quotation and to something Souljah had said in the music video of her song \"The Final Solution: Slavery's back in Effect\" (\"If there are any good white people, I haven't met them\").<ref>Anthony Lewis. '\"[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9E0CE6DD1031F93BA25755C0A964958260&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print Abroad at Home; Black and White],\" ''New York Times''.</ref> \"If you took the words 'white' and 'black,' and you reversed them, you might think [[David Duke]] was giving that speech,\" said Clinton.\n\nPrior to his appearance, Clinton's campaign staff had conducted an intense debate about how far he should go in distancing himself from Jackson, who was unpopular with moderate voters. When Souljah was invited to speak at the conference, Clinton's advisors saw their chance.\n{{external media| float = right| video1 = [https://www.c-span.org/video/?26613-1/rap-artists-response-clinton-remarks Sister Souljah's response to Gov. Bill Clinton's remarks, June 16, 1992], [[C-SPAN]]}}\nClinton's response was harshly criticized by Jackson, who said, \"Sister Souljah represents the feelings and hopes of a whole generation of people,\" and he claimed that she had been misquoted.<ref>Lewis, ''Op.cit.''</ref> Clinton was also criticized by some of the [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic Party]]'s other [[African American]] supporters.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kornacki |first=Steve |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/elections/1992-bill-clinton-builds-winning-coalition-jackson-diminished-n1029606 |title=1992: Bill Clinton builds a winning coalition, Jackson is diminished |work=[[NBC News]] |date=2019-07-29 |accessdate=2019-10-08 |quote=It was against this backdrop that Clinton delivered his \"Sister Souljah\" speech, which opened up a public war with Jackson. }}</ref> Souljah responded by denying she had ever made remarks promoting murder and accused Clinton of being a racist and a hypocrite because he had played golf at a country club that refused to admit black members until he decided to run for president earlier in the year;<ref name=uoooavt4>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1992-06-17/entertainment/ca-573_1_sister-souljah|title='I Do Not Advocate ... Murdering' : 'Raptivist' Sister Souljah Disputes Clinton Charge|author=Chuck Phillips|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=June 17, 1992|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref> Clinton acknowledged that he was once a member of an all-white Arkansas golf club early into his presidential campaign and publicly apologized.<ref name=uoooavt4 />  In response to the rebuttal, [[Paul Greenberg (journalist)|Paul Greenberg]], a progressive Arkansas journalist and longtime Clinton critic who dubbed the Arkansas Governor \"Slick Willie\" during his 1980 re-election bid,<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/choice/bill/greenberg.html American Frontline:Stories of Bill] Accessed August 25, 2014</ref> criticized Souljah for lying about what she said in an earlier interview with the Washington Post, accusing her of trying to fend off criticism \"with the savvy of an experienced pol.\" In the same article he compares her to [[Louis Farrakhan]], the leader of the [[Nation of Islam]].<ref>\n{{citation|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1992-06-19/news/9202240214_1_context-moral-rationality|title=Sister Souljah And The Irrational Rationality Of Hate|author=Paul Greenberg|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=June 19, 1992|accessdate=August 25, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Other examples==\nAs a [[candidate]] for the [[Republican Party (United States) presidential primaries, 2000|Republican nomination for president in 2000]], [[Governor of Texas|Texas Governor]] [[George W. Bush]] spoke before the [[American conservatism|conservative]] [[Manhattan Institute]] in October 1999 saying, \"Too often, on social issues, my party has painted an image of America slouching toward Gomorrah,\" quoting the title of a [[Slouching Towards Gomorrah|book]] by conservative [[jurist]] [[Robert Bork]].  Bush's comments were seen as a repudiation of the religious right and an attempt to appeal to moderate voters; commentator [[Charles Krauthammer]] called it \"an ever so subtle Sister Souljah on Robert Bork.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1999-10-11/news/9910110132_1_slouching-towards-gomorrah-borkian-robert-bork|title=Setting Himself Apart From Those Hard-core Conservatives|work=tribunedigital-chicagotribune|access-date=2017-09-25|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlso in the 2000 campaign for the Republican nomination, [[Arizona]] [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John McCain]] stated, \"Neither party should be defined by pandering to the outer reaches of American politics and the agents of intolerance, whether they be [[Louis Farrakhan]] or [[Al Sharpton]] on the left or [[Pat Robertson]] or [[Jerry Falwell]] on the right.\" This was similarly seen as a repudiation of the religious right; columnist [[Jacob Weisberg]] called it \"a pungent Sister Souljah moment.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Weisberg|first1=Jacob|title=McCain's Selective Outrage|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/ballot_box/2000/02/mccains_selective_outrage.html|website=Slate|publisher=Slate|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2008 United States presidential campaign]], [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee [[Barack Obama]] received much criticism for his association with his longtime Pastor [[Jeremiah Wright]], and Wright's pattern of racist statements. On April 29, Senator Obama distanced himself, in a well-received speech on racism, calling some of Wright's statements \"outrageous\" and \"a bunch of rants that aren't grounded in truth.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/04/29/AR2008042903173.html?hpid=topnews&hpid=topnews | work=The Washington Post | first1=Peter | last1=Slevin | first2=Darryl | last2=Fears | title=Obama Calls Minister's Comments 'Outrageous' | date=April 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Timraos\">Nick Timiraos and Jackie Calmes. ''Obama Denounces Ex-Pastor for 'Rants''', Wednesday, April 30, 2008, ppA1, A18.</ref> [[South Carolina]] [[United States House of Representatives|Congressman]] [[James Clyburn]] said of the speech, \"This, I think, offers Barack Obama his Sister Souljah moment\";<ref name=\"Timraos\"/> the speech was also described as \"more than a Sister Souljah moment\" by columnist [[Maureen Dowd]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/30/opinion/30dowd.html?_r=1&hp&oref=slogin | work=The New York Times | first=Maureen | last=Dowd | title=Praying and Preying | date=April 30, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn July 10, 2008, prior to a taping of ''[[Fox and Friends]]'', civil-rights activist [[Jesse Jackson]] was unwittingly caught by an open microphone whispering to a fellow interviewee, saying that then-candidate [[Barack Obama]] was talking down to black people and that he, Jackson, wanted to cut Obama's \"nuts off\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2008-07-09/politics/jesse.jackson.comment_1_obama-campaign-jesse-jackson-black-voters?_s=PM:POLITICS|title=Jackson apologizes for 'crude' Obama remarks|date=July 9, 2008|work=CNN Politics|accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref>  Jackson's son, Rep. [[Jesse Jackson, Jr.|Jesse Jackson Jr.]] of Illinois\u2014co-chair of Obama's presidential campaign\u2014publicly blasted his father's comments. [[Dan Balz]] called the comments an \"accidental Sister Souljah moment\" for Obama, since Jackson had distanced himself from the candidate, without Obama having to take a stand.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/44/2008/07/obamas-accidental-sister-soulj.html|title=Obama's Accidental Sister Souljah Moment|last=Balz|first=Dan|date=July 10, 2008|work=Washington Post|accessdate=11 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sister Souljah Moment}}\n[[Category:Political terminology]]\n[[Category:American political neologisms]]\n[[Category:Extremism]]\n[[Category:Centrism in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bill Clinton]]\n[[Category:1992 in American politics]]\n[[Category:History of hip hop]]\n[[Category:1992 Los Angeles riots]]\n", "name_user": "CoronaEditor", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sister_Souljah_moment"}
{"title_page": "Godfred Beko\u00e9", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Godfred Beko\u00e9\n| image       = \n| image_size  =  \n| caption     = \n| fullname    = Godfred Apraku Beko\u00e9\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1992|11|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Kumasi]], Ghana\n| height      = 1.76 m\n| currentclub = [[FCSR Haguenau|Haguenau]] \n| clubnumber  = \n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[RC Strasbourg|Strasbourg]]\n| years1 = 2009\u20132011 |clubs1 = [[RC Strasbourg|Strasbourg B]]                   |caps1 = 32 |goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2011\u20132013 |clubs2 = [[En Avant de Guingamp|Guingamp B]]              |caps2 = 8  |goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2013\u20132014 |clubs3 = [[Olympiakos Nicosia]]                           |caps3 = 16 |goals3 = 5\n| years4 = 2014      |clubs4 = [[PSFC Chernomorets Burgas|Chernomorets Burgas]] |caps4 = 9  |goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2015      |clubs5 = [[CS Gaz Metan Media\u0219|Gaz Metan Media\u0219]]         |caps5 = 6  |goals5 = 0\n| years6 = 2017\u20132019 |clubs6 = [[SC Schiltigheim|Schiltigheim]]                 |caps6 = 57 |goals6 = 12\n| years7 = 2019\u2013     |clubs7 = [[FCSR Haguenau|Haguenau]]                       |caps7 = 9  |goals7 = 0\n| pcupdate = 20:37, 27 November 2019 (UTC)\n}}\n'''Godfred Beko\u00e9'''  (born 12 November 1992) is a [[Ghana]]ian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[FCSR Haguenau]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]].\n\n==External links==\n*{{RomanianSoccer|old_id=p/godfred-bekoe}}\n*{{Soccerway|godfred-bekoe/169693}}\n*[http://www.futbol-talentos.es/Godfred_Apraku_Beko__-3_7-46938-3.html Godfred Beko\u00e9] at futbol-talentos.es\n*[http://cfd.com.cy/index.php?person=1263 Godfred Beko\u00e9] at cfd.com.cy\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bekoe, Godfred}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kumasi]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian footballers]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:RC Strasbourg Alsace players]]\n[[Category:En Avant de Guingamp players]]\n[[Category:SC Schiltigheim players]]\n[[Category:Olympiakos Nicosia players]]\n[[Category:PFC Chernomorets Burgas players]]\n[[Category:CS Gaz Metan Media\u0219 players]]\n[[Category:Championnat National 2 players]]\n[[Category:First Professional Football League (Bulgaria) players]]\n[[Category:Liga I players]]\n[[Category:Cypriot Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in Romania]]\n[[Category:Ghanaian expatriate sportspeople in France]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Romania]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Godfred Beko\u00e9\n| image       = \n| image_size  =  \n| caption     = \n| fullname    = Godfred Apraku Beko\u00e9\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1992|11|12}}\n| birth_place = [[Kumasi]], Ghana\n| height      = {{convert|1.76|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| currentclub = [[FCSR Haguenau|Haguenau]] \n| clubnumber  = \n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = \n| youthclubs1 = [[RC Strasbourg|Strasbourg]]\n| years1 = 2009\u20132011 |clubs1 = [[RC Strasbourg|Strasbourg B]]                   |caps1 = 32 |goals1 = 2\n| years2 = 2011\u20132013 |clubs2 = [[En Avant de Guingamp|Guingamp B]]              |caps2 = 8  |goals2 = 1\n| years3 = 2013\u20132014 |clubs3 = [[Olympiakos Nicosia]]                           |caps3 = 16 |goals3 = 5\n| years4 = 2014      |clubs4 = [[PSFC Chernomorets Burgas|Chernomorets Burgas]] |caps4 = 9  |goals4 = 2\n| years5 = 2015      |clubs5 = [[